    {
      "id": "1fb72b30ad5b739243822c1ccef5d1b3e78f9efb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 112,
        "name": "Oleg Drokin",
        "email": "green@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "green"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-26 17:41:35.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nis there an impact on performance from this across the board atomic inc in service handler?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "c74556d30ae5ec1fe2dceca96c31d16ee5a043ee",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-27 01:34:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nHi Oleg,\n\nThat's a good point. But I guess atomic increasement will not cause performance problem here.\n\nIn order to check the performance of atomic increasement, I write following quick patch. It turns out that we can do atomic increasement more than 100,000,000 times per second. RPC rate is not able to reach even 0.1% of this rate, i.e. 100,000 RPC/s. Typically, the RPC rate of a OSS who can provide throughput of 1GB/s is about 1000 PRC/s. I know my estimation is far from accurate. But maybe it makes sense? What's your opinion?\n\nHere is the patch. Please do not run it on production environment because it will crash the kernel when umount. :-)\n\nIndex: lustre-release.git/lustre/ptlrpc/service.c\n===================================================================\n--- lustre-release.git.orig/lustre/ptlrpc/service.c\n+++ lustre-release.git/lustre/ptlrpc/service.c\n@@ -779,6 +779,15 @@ ptlrpc_service_summary_fini(struct ptlrp\n        EXIT;\n }\n\n+static int summary_inc(void *arg)\n+{\n+       struct ptlrpc_service_summary *summary = arg;\n+       while(1) {\n+               cfs_atomic_inc(&summary->ss_rpc_number);\n+       }\n+       return 0;\n+}\n+\n static int ptlrpc_service_summary_init(struct ptlrpc_service *svc)\n {\n        struct ptlrpc_service_summary *summary = &svc->srv_summary;\n@@ -809,6 +818,7 @@ static int ptlrpc_service_summary_init(s\n                      cfs_time_seconds(summary->ss_timeout) +\n                      cfs_time_current());\n\n+       kthread_run(summary_inc, summary, \"summary_inc\");\n        RETURN(0);\n fail:\n        ptlrpc_service_summary_fini(svc);",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "ef5867854ed887fd0a0fe4333c5911e6418ba83f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 176,
        "name": "Liang Zhen",
        "email": "liang.zhen@intel.com",
        "username": "liangzhen",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-07-29 05:48:02.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4: No score\n\nI think Oleg's concern is that performance issue if atomic operations performance under race, e.g. many service threads (all CPUs) try to change it at the same time. \nWe have made many efforts to reduce number of global locks/atomics, and we don't want to lose performance improvements by adding new global lock/atomic.\nThis can be avoid by two different options:\n- use per-cpu-partition counter instead of global counter, for example, put this counter in ptlrpc_service_part instead of ptlrpc_service, this will require more changes then this patch because we have to calculate for each partition then summarise results.\n- make this counter to be tunable and it's disabled by default, user can turn it on at runtime via proc or sysctl, this is more like a workaround but it requires less change.\nPersonally, I will be OK with either way.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "f283bad1bdde6756817d0fc87145218870d30059",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 337,
        "name": "Li Xi",
        "email": "lixi@ddn.com",
        "username": "LiX"
      },
      "date": "2013-07-29 07:29:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nHi Liang Zhen,\n\nThank you very much for the detailed explanation.\n\nI've changed the codes in the first way. Please check whether it is what you mean.\n\nThanks!",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 4
    },
